    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, return a compact summary: (1) total row count, (2) min(timestamp) and max(timestamp), (3) distinct cmdb_id values and their row counts (limit to top 20 by count), and (4) distinct KPI/trace/log names and their row counts (for metric.csv use kpi_name, for trace.csv use trace_name, for log.csv use log_name). For each distinct-name list, limit output to top 50 items. Return results as plain text/CSV-like rows (no plots) and keep outputs small."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step loaded and summarized all four telemetry files. Findings: metric.csv (152,352 rows) and trace.csv (31,536 rows) cover the incident interval 2022-03-21 21:30:00+08:00 to 2022-03-21 21:59:00+08:00. metric.csv contains many container and node KPIs (examples show many container.node-5.* metrics and numerous pod metrics such as frontend-0/1/2 and various services). trace.csv shows per-service trace features for frontend and downstream services. log.csv contains two log types (log.error_count, log.row_count) across many services. error_logs.csv contains 743 rows with messages like \"severity: warning, message: failed to retrieve...\" and entries concentrated on frontend-2, frontend-1, frontend-0. These observations suggest frontend pods have warning/error logs during the window and node/container KPIs exist for analysis, but we have not yet computed global thresholds or identified metric anomalies. Next we must compute global thresholds (P95 and P5) per component-KPI on the full series (before filtering), then detect anomalies inside the incident window to narrow suspects.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "On metric.csv do the following (compute on the FULL series, then filter to the incident window 2022-03-21 21:30:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 22:00:00+08:00):\n1) For each distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 and P5 using all available rows in metric.csv for that pair.\n2) Using those thresholds, count the number of anomaly points inside the incident window where value >= P95 (call these 'high' anomalies) or value <= P5 (call these 'low' anomalies). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) also compute earliest anomaly timestamp in the window, max and min values observed in the window, and whether anomalies are 'high', 'low', or 'both'.\n3) Return the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs sorted by anomaly count (descending) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, p5, anomaly_count, anomaly_direction, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Limit rows to 20. Keep output compact (CSV-like or tabular)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous executor run computed global thresholds and anomaly counts per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and returned the top-20 series by anomaly_count. Most of the top entries are static/container-spec metrics for shippingservice2-0 (e.g., container_spec_memory_limit_MB, container_start_time_seconds, container_spec_cpu_period) that have p95 == p5 and constant values over the incident window. These constant/config metrics produce 30 anomaly points (one per minute) but are not meaningful for runtime fault detection. Also, error_logs.csv is concentrated on frontend pods (frontend-2, frontend-1, frontend-0) indicating frontends reported warnings; trace.csv contains service-level trace metrics (error_rate, duration_p95/mean) for frontend->downstream chains. To proceed correctly we must exclude constant/config metrics and focus on variable runtime KPIs. Next we should produce a compact list of the top non-constant metric anomalies (i.e., where p95 != p5 and values vary in-window) so we can identify candidate faulty components and then follow with trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Recompute metric anomalies (use the FULL series to compute global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name), then filter to the incident window 2022-03-21 21:30:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 21:59:00+08:00). From that result, return the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs sorted by anomaly_count (descending) but only include rows that satisfy all of: (1) p95 != p5, (2) max_value_in_window != min_value_in_window, and (3) anomaly_count > 0. For each row return these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, p5, anomaly_count, anomaly_direction, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, unique_values_count_in_window. Limit output to 20 rows and present compact tabular/CSV-like text."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds and found many metric series with persistent minute-by-minute anomalies across the 21:30–22:00 window. Many top anomalies were constant/container-spec KPIs (should be ignored). After filtering out constant series, the remaining candidate anomalies include container-level runtime KPIs (memory_mapped_file, file_descriptors, sockets, fs_writes, memory usage, threads) for multiple services (checkoutservice-2, paymentservice2-0, adservice-1/2, frontend-2, productcatalogservice2-0, etc.). Error_logs.csv is concentrated on frontend-2, frontend-1, frontend-0 (743 rows) with a repeated warning message. To narrow to the actual two failure events we must determine the precise minutes when user-facing errors occurred (likely from error_logs and log.error_count), then correlate those minutes with trace-level error_rate/latency anomalies and with the metric KPIs at the same times. Next step: find the minute-level distribution of error logs and aggregated log.error_count/row_count over the incident window so we can identify the two peak failure minutes to analyze further with traces and metrics.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Aggregate error_logs.csv and log.csv within the incident window 2022-03-21 21:30:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 21:59:00+08:00 and return compact tables:\n1) From error_logs.csv: group by timestamp (minute) and cmdb_id, count messages. Return top 20 rows sorted by count desc with columns: timestamp (minute), cmdb_id, count.\n2) Also return total error_logs count per minute (summed across cmdb_id) for the window (show all minutes where count>0, sorted by timestamp ascending).\n3) From log.csv: filter to log_name in {\"log.error_count\",\"log.row_count\"}. For each minute (timestamp) and each log_name, sum value across all cmdb_ids; return rows (timestamp, log_name, summed_value) for the full window sorted by timestamp ascending.\nLimit outputs to at most 60 rows in total and present compact CSV-like/tabular text; do not print full raw files."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed metric and trace global thresholds and scanned anomalies across the 21:30–21:59 UTC+8 window. Metric anomalies (after excluding constant/config metrics) point to multiple container-level resource KPIs (memory_mapped_file, file_descriptors, sockets, fs_writes, memory usage, threads) across several services. Error logs and aggregated log.error_count show sustained errors across the 30 minutes, dominated by frontend pods (frontend-2 and frontend-1). Trace-level anomalies for frontend-origin traces are mostly constant-zero error_rate series and many 'both' flags, so they produced many false positives. To locate the two distinct failures we need to identify the two most significant minutes (peaks) within the window where user-facing errors spiked, and then examine traces and metrics at those exact minutes to find the downstream faulty service and the resource reason. The next step is therefore to extract the top 2 minutes by total error_log count and show the per-cmdb breakdown and log.error_count sums for those minutes so we can pick minute-level targets for deeper trace and metric inspection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Within the incident window 2022-03-21 21:30:00+08:00 through 2022-03-21 21:59:00+08:00, aggregate error_logs.csv by minute and identify the top 2 minutes by total error message count. For each of these two minutes return compact information: (1) timestamp_min (UTC+8), (2) total_error_count, (3) top 10 cmdb_id counts for that minute as pairs cmdb_id(count) separated by commas, and (4) the summed log.error_count from log.csv for that minute. Present results as up to 2 CSV-like rows with columns: timestamp_min,total_error_count,top_cmdbs,log_error_count_sum. Limit output to these two rows only."
}

{
    "analysis": "We identified the two peak failure minutes within the incident window: 2022-03-21T21:32:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21T21:34:00+08:00 (each with 35 error messages, mainly from frontend pods). We have metric-level anomaly scans across the full 30-minute window that flagged many persistent per-minute anomalies; after filtering out constant/config metrics, candidate runtime anomalies include container-level KPIs (memory_mapped_file, file_descriptors, sockets, fs_writes_MB, memory usage, threads) across multiple services. Trace-level scans for frontend-origin traces were noisy because many error_rate series are constant zeros; a few duration metrics have small variability but require per-minute inspection. To localize the root cause for each of the two failures, we now need minute-level correlation: which component-KPI series actually breached global thresholds exactly at each peak minute (21:32 and 21:34), and which downstream service traces showed error/latency abnormalities at those same minutes. This will narrow candidate root-cause components for each failure before we inspect logs for resource-specific error messages.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv (compute global P95 and P5 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) on the FULL series), extract metric values at the two minutes 2022-03-21T21:32:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21T21:34:00+08:00 (UTC+8). For each of these two minutes, return the top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs that breach thresholds at that minute (value >= P95 or value <= P5). Exclude pairs where P95 == P5 (constant/config metrics). For each returned row include: minute, cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, p5, value_at_minute, anomaly_direction ('high' or 'low'), abs_diff (absolute difference between value and the threshold it breached). Sort rows per minute by abs_diff descending and limit to 20 rows per minute. Present results in compact CSV-like/tabular text (max 40 rows total)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have identified two peak failure minutes (2022-03-21T21:32:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21T21:34:00+08:00) with error logs dominated by frontend pods (frontend-2, frontend-1, frontend-0). Metric anomaly scans (global P95/P5 computed on full series) show at 21:32 very large deviation for frontend-2 container_memory_cache and several node filesystem/inode and container memory_rss spikes on productcatalogservice/checkouts; at 21:34 prominent deviations include container memory_rss spikes (currencyservice-1, frontend-0, currencyservice2-0), mesh source/destination metrics, and productcatalogservice trace row_count increases (frontend→productcatalogservice). Trace anomalies are mostly elevated frontend-origin row_count into productcatalogservice and related services. According to the localization rules, the root cause should be chosen from the faulty components identified by metrics first, and when multiple same-level components are faulty, use traces/logs to find the most downstream faulty component. At 21:32 the largest absolute metric deviation is frontend-2.container_memory_cache (suggesting frontend-2 memory pressure coincident with the first failure minute), and error logs are concentrated on frontend-2 — making frontend-2 a strong candidate for the first failure. At 21:34 traces implicate productcatalogservice (elevated row_count) while metrics show memory_rss and mesh deviations across several services (currencyservice, frontend, productcatalogservice); we need finer per-KPI inspection to decide whether the second failure root cause is a productcatalogservice pod or another service (e.g., currencyservice). To proceed safely (and comply with rule to only query known KPIs), we must first enumerate available KPI names for the top candidate cmdb_ids so we can target the correct KPI series for consecutive-anomaly/fault detection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, list distinct kpi_name values for these cmdb_ids: frontend-2, productcatalogservice-0, productcatalogservice-1, productcatalogservice-2, currencyservice-1, and frontend-0. For each cmdb_id return up to 50 distinct kpi_name entries and the row count per kpi_name (sorted by count desc). Present compact CSV-like tables per cmdb_id (limit total output)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through preprocessing, global-threshold calculation (P95/P5 on full series), anomaly detection, and preliminary fault identification. Key facts derived so far:\n- Two peak failure minutes from error logs: 2022-03-21T21:32:00+08:00 and 2022-03-21T21:34:00+08:00 (each 35 error messages), primarily from frontend pods (frontend-2, frontend-1, frontend-0).\n- At 21:32 the strongest metric fault is a consecutive high segment on frontend-2.container.node-5.container_memory_cache starting at 2022-03-21T21:32:00+08:00 (2 minutes) with very large abs deviation (~1.96e6 above P95). Error logs are concentrated on frontend-2 at that time. Per rules (most significant deviation across levels), frontend-2 (container-level memory pressure) is a strong candidate for the first failure — occurrence time 2022-03-21T21:32:00+08:00 and root cause reason: container memory/memory_cache spike.\n- For the second peak minute 21:34, metric and trace anomalies are more distributed: container_memory_rss spikes (currencyservice-1, frontend-0, currencyservice2-0) and mesh/trace row_count increases toward productcatalogservice. Our earliest-anomaly check showed currencyservice2-0.container_memory_rss has a 2-minute high segment that includes 21:34 (segment 21:33–21:34), while other prominent series either had earliest anomalies at different minutes or did not include 21:34 in their earliest segment. This makes currencyservice2-0 a leading candidate for the second failure, but we need confirmation using trace anomalies at 21:34 to determine whether currencyservice2-0 is the most downstream faulty container/service (or if productcatalogservice traces indicate productcatalogservice is downstream-faulty). Trace scans earlier were noisy (many constant-zero error_rate series). We therefore need a focused check: which trace series at 21:34 breach their global thresholds (P95/P5) and which services are most significantly deviating at that exact minute. This will allow us to decide whether the second failure root cause is currencyservice2-0 (container memory RSS) or another service that appears downstream in traces at 21:34.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the exact minute 2022-03-21T21:34:00+08:00 (use global P95/P5 computed on the FULL trace series), scan trace.csv and return trace series that breach thresholds at that minute (value >= P95 or value <= P5). Exclude trace series where P95 == P5. Return top 20 rows sorted by absolute deviation from the breached threshold (abs_diff) descending. For each row include these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95, p5, value_at_minute, anomaly_direction('high' or 'low'), abs_diff. Present results as a compact CSV-like table limited to 20 rows."
}

